rm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=54.topic&index=41>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_cry.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Rhetoric v. Reality</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I am pro-choice - You choose to practice safe sex or you choose to accept the consequences(not punishment- con sequence.) of your actions. If I drive drunk and kill someone, it doesnt matter what the reasons behind it are. I did something and there are natural consequences of those actions.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I operate from the definition of ‘choice’ as being more choices.  Once you limit choices, you become pro-control-others.  If you hit someone and kill them with your car, driving at the speed limit in clear conditions, should you be held to the same punishment as a drunk with no license in an unregistered car that intentionally runs down his ex?  But you chose to drive the car!  You are just as guilty as the guy who did it intentionally!  Burn them all!<br>
<br>
This argument doesn’t work.  It assumes a one-size-fits-all solution to a problem that by its very nature is fraught with case-by-case conditions.  What if the family has a defective child and wants to carry it?  Does the gov’t have any right to tell them they HAVE to abort?  If the family can choose to keep a defective child and raise them in a loving and nurtured environment, how is that inherently worse than a welfare mom with more kids than she wanted faced with yet another she can’t handle?  If the birth will devastate the lives of others, impoverishing the quality of their lives, I see that as just as bad as being defective.  A miserable existence is a miserable existence.  Handicapped kids and adults are indeed loving and wonderful people.  Their needs are insanely high and I don’t think I am such a good person I could face the rest of my life caring for a 6 foot tall infant.  I worked in ARC centers and know, they are loving, and frustrating, and an incredible drain on their parents, emotionally, physically and financially.  It really takes a special and dedicated person to face that for a lifetime.  I could only do it for a few hours a day a few times a week.  They face it 24x7.  I applaud their strength and understand anyone faced with it that knows their limits and chooses responsibly not to take it on.  I have also seen those who cannot handle it, and their consequences.<br>
<br>
Every president since Reagan has signed another bill into law making 3rd trimester abortions less and less possible for any reason.  The argument that you want them controlled falls flat because they are already too strictly controlled.  Even in the cases of rape or incest or severe birth defects, the lines are drawn against arbitrary political scratches in the sand, as evidenced by the testimony of Double Latte.  Even when it is warranted, it is almost impossible to do, and they make it harder and more painful on the mother.  Causing more suffering is not the right of the legislature, nor the ‘free speech’ of the protestor’s outside a clinic.  No one enters into it lightly, and the ones who do would still find a way.<br>
